T1  - What Comes to Mind*
PY  - 2010
Y1  - 2010/11/01
DO  - 10.1162/qjec.2010.125.4.1399
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 125
IS  - 4
SP  - 1399
EP  - 1433
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - We present a model of intuitive inference, called “local thinking,” in which an agent combines data received from the external world with information retrieved from memory to evaluate a hypothesis. In this model, selected and limited recall of information follows a version of the representativeness heuristic. The model can account for some of the evidence on judgment biases, including conjunction and disjunction fallacies, but also for several anomalies related to demand for insurance.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1162/qjec.2010.125.4.1399
ER  - 



